#) The has() Method:
    - The has() method returns true if a specified value exists in a set.
        // Create a Set
        const letters = new Set(["a","b","c"]);

        // Does the Set contain "d"?
        answer = letters.has("d");  // false


#) The forEach() Method:
    - The forEach() method invokes a function for each Set element:
        // Create a Set
        const letters = new Set(["a","b","c"]);

        // List all entries
        let text = "";
        letters.forEach (function(value) {
            text += value;
        })
        document.getElementById("3").innerHTML = ` ${text}`;   //abc


#) The values() Method:
    - The values() method returns an Iterator object with the values in a Set:
        // Create a Set
        const letters = new Set(["a","b","c"]);

        // Get all Values
        const myIterator = letters.values();    // [object Set Iterator]

        // List all Values
        let text = "";
        for (const entry of myIterator) {
            text += entry;
        }
        document.getElementById("3").innerHTML = ` ${text}`;   //abc

            or,
        
        // Create a Set
        const letters = new Set(["a","b","c"]);

        // List all Iterators with Values
        let text = "";
        for (const entry of letters.values()) {
            text += entry;
        }
        document.getElementById("3").innerHTML = ` ${text}`;   //abc


#) The keys() Method:
    - The keys() method returns an Iterator object with the values in a Set:
    - 💡unlike objects and Arrays, a Set has no keys, so keys() returns the same as values(). This
        makes Sets compatible with Maps.
        // Create a Set
        const letters = new Set(["a","b","c"]);

        // Get all Iterators with Values
        const myIterator = letters.keys();    // [object Set Iterator]

        // List all Values
        let text = "";
        for (const entry of myIterator) {
            text += entry;
        }
        document.getElementById("3").innerHTML = ` ${text}`;   //abc

           or,
        
        // Create a Set
        const letters = new Set(["a","b","c"]);

        // List all Iterators with Values
        let text = "";
        for (const entry of letters.keys()) {
            text += entry;
        }
        document.getElementById("3").innerHTML = ` ${text}`;   //abc


#) The entries() Method:
    - The entries() method returns an Iterator with [value,value] pairs from a Set.
    - 💡The entries() method is supposed to return a [key,value] pair from an object. A Set has no keys,
        so the entries() method returns [value,value].
    - This makes Sets compatible with Maps.
        // get all values
        const iterator2 = mySet.entries();   // [object Set Iterator]
        // list all values
        let text3 = "";
        for (const entry of iterator2) {
            text3 += entry + "<br>";
        }
        document.getElementById("5").innerHTML = `[value, value]: <br> ${text3}`;   // [value, value]:
                                                                                        a,a
                                                                                        b,b
                                                                                        c,c

